metadata.name: Imaginary Resonances #391
metadata.description:
Some people describe creative coding as 'Computer Magick' and I agree, there is some degree of mysticism involved. Taking a physical phenomena and distorting it so that is no longer real is what Imaginary Resonances is about.

There is a surface and sand is dropped on it. The surface vibrates and ushers the sand into patterns. What kind of sound could have made the surface vibrate like that?

The algorithm behind Imaginary Resonances is simple variation on Chladni figures: figures that arise when sand is dropped on a vibrating surface.

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with p5

metadata.name: Tangentum #220
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Subdivision: forms and feelings #80
Lucky Oracles #261
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts

metadata.name: Life has no scores #56
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop “Nothing comes from nothing”. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press ‘2’ to save png.

metadata.name: Univercell #13
metadata.description:
⚗🦠🌌✨

The center of a digital, quantified space emits 2 560 000 particles through a sequence of expansions, contractions and perturbations. 🌌

Once formed, the evolution of the Univercell can be observed through a series of animations in the manner of a documentary. 🎥

Each Univercell is a unique random and deterministic composition. 🔮

(Click ‘open’ and go fullscreen for best experience !)

🎄🌟🪐🌈☀




-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a 1920x1920 PNG bitmap and an infinite animation.

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 → 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration.

The physics algorithms take around 20 seconds to generate one Univercell. During generation, a progress indication in percentage is displayed.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL
- Unique generative and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Unlimited duration (no loop) / 6 documentary animations
- 20 seconds internal algorithm variations

-----
* Controls *

Keyboard "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

⚗ Empiric mode (empiric=on / see URL modifiers below)
Wheel/pinch : zoom in/out to observe the Univercell on different scales
Right click + drag : move the observation area
Keyboard "R" : enable automatic rotation of view

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&empiric=on"
Turn off animations and display a Univercell that can be manually explored.

"&demo=on"
Reduce the cinematics duration to 5 seconds. Allows faster cycling through documentary phases.

"&random=on"
Randomize documentary sequences order.


-----
@HAL09999 – December 21st, 2022

metadata.name: Attractor #335
metadata.description:
People are often drawn together over shared interest, and through their connections to those interests they find connections with others. Attractor is a visualization of community, a central interest bringing people together, pushing past their walls, bad habits, and traumas. The image is meant to be deceiving in its focus on the attractor, where the true focus is on the overlaps and complex defenses we build around ourselves. Those defenses can make us and those connections into more beautiful, ornate structures, or keep us distant from those around us. Sometimes focusing on a shared attractor is the only way we can let down our guard.

Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle the grain for printing or personal preference
Press ‘p’ to save a higher quality .png
Created with p5.js and chroma.js
